TOPIC: Promises vs Async/Await in JavaScript

What it is: Both handle asynchronous operations — code that takes time to complete (API calls, file reads). Think of it like ordering food: you don't wait at the counter, you get a buzzer (Promise) and come back when ready.

The problem: JavaScript runs one thing at a time. Without async tools, slow operations would freeze your entire app.

Simple example:
// Promise
fetch('/api/data').then(res => res.json()).then(data => console.log(data))

// Async/Await (same thing, cleaner to read)
async function getData() {
  const res = await fetch('/api/data')
  const data = await res.json()
  console.log(data)
}

When to use: Async/await for new code (cleaner). Promises when chaining multiple async operations or using Promise.all().
